<pre>Hi,

In message &quot;<A HREF="/cgi-bin/scat.rb/ruby/ruby-talk/2770">[ruby-talk:02770]</A>&quot;
    on 00/05/11, Andrew Hunt &lt;Andy / Toolshed.Com&gt; writes:

|<span style="color: #007700;">I'm trying to install mod_ruby 0.17 with the latest Ruby from CVS,</span>
|<span style="color: #007700;">and I'm running into a spot of trouble.</span>
|
|<span style="color: #007700;">Using the Makefile produced by Makefile.rb, the module fails to load --</span>
|<span style="color: #007700;">it complains that:</span>
|
|<span style="color: #007700;">Cannot load /toolshed/local/libexec/mod_ruby.so into server: </span>
|<span style="color: #007700;">/toolshed/local/libexec/mod_ruby.so: undefined symbol: rb_io_close</span>
|<span style="color: #007700;">/toolshed/local/bin/apachectl start: httpd could not be started</span>
|
|<span style="color: #007700;">And indeed, there's nothing in the Makefile that indicates Ruby should </span>
|<span style="color: #007700;">be linked in.  So I thought I'd be daring and add libruby.a into the </span>
|<span style="color: #007700;">shared obejct link.</span>

Hmm, Makefile.RB should find the place for libruby.a or libruby.so
from compilation information, which is placed in rbconfig.rb.

My Makefile contains the line:

  LIBRUBYARG = -L/usr/lib -lruby

to link the interpreter.

							matz.
